</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/unobbynoblittlun.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nobbynob Littlun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www2.kalenda.com/andrew/stuff/ezboard-use/alarm.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(12/17/01 2:14:11 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www2.kalenda.com/andrew/stuff/ezboard-use/zz000082.bmp WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Quick question for Warrior types </span><hr size=1> Actually I would have top disagree; fast weapons generate significantly more taunt, which is why people choose, say, Lammies, over the far superior damage/delay ratio of the Wurmslayer. I'd imagine this is because a certain amount of taunt is created simply by swinging your weapon at something; otherwise, nothing would attack if you missed the first couple of times you try to hit it, but they do aggro if you walk up to, say, a froglok, and it's just standing there and you swing a couple times; damage is not necessary. So I guess every attack has a base amount of taunt, and damage adds to that. Of course this is just conjecture as to why fast weapons often taunt better than weapons that may have better damage/delay ratio.<br>
<br>
Of course if you're not tanking a lot (i.e. monk, rogue, ranger, beastlord) then you want the better damage/delay ratio... <p>~<b><a href="mailto:gnomewarriah@yahoogroups.com">Nobbynob Littlun</a></b>, Gnome Watchwoman
